<!-- SECTION [11763-11807] -->
<a name="gnu"></a><h3> GNU </h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
 Acronyme de &ldquo;GNU&rsquo;s Not Unix&rdquo; = GNU n&rsquo;est pas Unix
</p>

<p>
Le projet GNU a été lancé en 1984 par Richard M Stallman, un développeur de logiciels au laboratoire d&rsquo;Intelligence Artificielle du Massachussets Institute of Technology. Le but de ce projet est d&rsquo;offrir des logiciels libres de haute qualité. 
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [11808-12123] -->
<a name="groupe"></a><h3> Groupe </h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
 Le concept de groupe d&rsquo;utilisateurs provient d&rsquo;Unix. Les groupes existent en général afin de faciliter le partage des ressources entre utilisateurs appartenant à un même groupe.  Ainsi, alors que la plupart des fichiers de votre projet appartiennent à leur propriétaire, ils font également partie du groupe de travail, ce qui permet à chacun des membres de pouvoir les utiliser.
</p>

<p>
<em>Voir aussi Accès &amp; permissions.</em>
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [12124-12567] -->
<a name="h"></a><h2> H </h2>
<div class="level2">

</div>
<!-- SECTION [12568-12581] -->
<a name="hard_link"></a><h3> Hard link </h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
 To the contrary of the symlink (symbolic link), here the actual data on disk is pointed to by more than one directory entry.
</p>

<p>
A symbolic link is merely a file that refers to another file; a hard link is actually the same exact information, located at the same spot on the disk.
</p>

<p>
With a hard link, you can pick any one of the instances of the file, and delete all the rest, and it&rsquo;ll still exist; with symbolic links, you can delete the target file and then all the symbolic links to it will point to a non-existent file!
</p>

<p>
But it&rsquo;s much easier to distinguish between an itty-bitty symbolic link and the target file, than the original doc and any other hard link to it. In fact, it&rsquo;s impossible, since they are the exact same thing!
</p>

<p>
Hard links are becoming more and more obsolete, in favor of soft links. I strongly suggest you use symlinks, unless you know what you are doing.
</p>

<p>
(the reference count , ie the number of hard links can be seen on the second column of an ls -l.
</p>

<p>
If you delete a file with a &gt;1 reference count, it means the data is still stored somewhere, and accessible through another hard link,
</p>

<p>
if the reference count ==1, and you delete the file, the data will be lost and the space will actually be freed.
</p>

<p>
Don&rsquo;t mention reference counts smaller than 1 they are bad news <img src="/smileys/icon_smile.gif" align="middle" alt=":-)" />
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [12582-13897] -->
<a name="hth"></a><h2> HTH </h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
 Hope This Helps <em>...que l&rsquo;on peut traduire par &ldquo;En espérant vous avoir aidé&rdquo;</em>
</p>

</div>
